00:31:28.240 --> 00:31:31.433
and suddenly there’s
an intermission number

500
00:31:31.458 --> 00:31:35.005
where the villagers go,
"Have you heard?" and so on.

501
00:31:35.281 --> 00:31:41.420
Finally, when the song ended,
you still continued with that scene.

502
00:31:43.005 --> 00:31:48.053
- I used it as a device
so there'll be time for set change.

503
00:31:48.438 --> 00:31:52.586
It doesn't need to be changed.
Just remove everything.

504
00:31:52.611 --> 00:31:55.899
You could remove
that whole part

505
00:31:57.449 --> 00:32:02.446
because it lessens
the momentum.

506
00:32:03.117 --> 00:32:05.156
Skip to the part
where they're caught...

507
00:32:05.211 --> 00:32:08.977
They were caught.
Then Jaime got ahold of Sarah,

508
00:32:09.125 --> 00:32:13.290
He already had her,
but suddenly the people appear,

509
00:32:13.352 --> 00:32:16.735
and so many rumors have spread.

510
00:32:16.797 --> 00:32:20.336
Then you cut back
to Jaime still holding her.

511
00:32:20.906 --> 00:32:23.024
Just remove it
and go forward.

512
00:32:26.293 --> 00:32:31.129
If you want it to be short,
maybe with Mauro or whoever,

513
00:32:31.226 --> 00:32:34.609
one blackout is enough.

514
00:32:34.696 --> 00:32:36.260
How about you?

515
00:32:36.808 --> 00:32:38.007
Ellen.

516
00:32:38.338 --> 00:32:42.015
- For me, it just seems like...

517
00:32:42.084 --> 00:32:45.893
- I think the two characters,
although this happens in real life,

518
00:32:45.925 --> 00:32:49.735
seemed inconsistent.

519
00:32:49.834 --> 00:32:52.609
- Like the priest, who was taking up something else,

520
00:32:52.641 --> 00:32:55.437
but when told to become a priest, he agrees.

521
00:32:55.476 --> 00:32:57.953
- Then he came back
and learned Sarah was raped

522
00:32:57.986 --> 00:33:01.930
- so he decided to leave priesthood for her,
but in the end, he gave her up.

523
00:33:02.027 --> 00:33:03.886
- Doesn't it seem so...

524
00:33:04.115 --> 00:33:07.210
- What’s the growth in his character?

525
00:33:07.310 --> 00:33:11.405
- He's always been inconsistent
with what he really wants.

526
00:33:11.659 --> 00:33:13.292
- It’s the same for the woman.

527
00:33:13.338 --> 00:33:16.441
- She really loved this guy,
but then she got raped.

528
00:33:16.475 --> 00:33:20.332
- She couldn't tell anyone,
and so she agreed to get married.

529
00:33:21.325 --> 00:33:23.755
- But she still liked Victor.

530
00:33:23.807 --> 00:33:25.965
- And in the end,
she came back to Jaime.

531
00:33:26.004 --> 00:33:29.427
- Their resolve
always seems to waver.

532
00:33:29.476 --> 00:33:31.996
- So I don't know about their growth as characters.

533
00:33:32.137 --> 00:33:35.678
- Or did they just accept the traps?
That's the ending?

534
00:33:35.739 --> 00:33:38.435
- But you started the play

535
00:33:38.661 --> 00:33:44.294
with the impression
that it’d be a rebellious play.

536
00:33:44.606 --> 00:33:49.034
- That it would turn the tables

537
00:33:49.066 --> 00:33:52.681
turn the tables on the church,
on politics, and on love.

538
00:33:52.761 --> 00:33:54.571
- Because I remember
when you were talking about this

539
00:33:54.630 --> 00:33:58.330
at its early stages that it was okay
to love more than one person.

540
00:33:58.355 --> 00:34:03.894
- That you’re going to turn around
the concepts of love, politics, church.

541
00:34:03.971 --> 00:34:05.635
- And yet the ending,

542
00:34:07.119 --> 00:34:12.095
it went back
to the sanctity of marriage,

543
00:34:12.164 --> 00:34:15.697
the oath of priesthood,

544
00:34:15.758 --> 00:34:20.111
even if he never really chose
that as a vocation.

545
00:34:20.523 --> 00:34:23.304
- That's what confuses me.

546
00:34:23.442 --> 00:34:29.388
- I was set up to believe
that you’d turn the tables on institutions

547
00:34:30.592 --> 00:34:32.285
but in the end...

548
00:34:35.637 --> 00:34:39.231
- Based on Mauro's
criticism and comments,

549
00:34:40.395 --> 00:34:44.981
it's a very pretentious society,
full of hypocrisies.

550
00:34:45.112 --> 00:34:46.382
- Yet in the end,

551
00:34:46.702 --> 00:34:53.852
they stick to all the trappings
of the church, of marriage.

552
00:34:54.085 --> 00:34:55.749
- That's where I'm confused.

553
00:34:56.674 --> 00:34:59.853
- I thought

554
00:34:59.935 --> 00:35:04.103
of all those trappings

555
00:35:04.197 --> 00:35:06.058
as the hypocrisies themselves.

556
00:35:07.809 --> 00:35:14.034
- You know it’s wrong,
but we still tolerate it.

557
00:35:14.334 --> 00:35:18.040
- "I'll just live with it" kind of thinking.

558
00:35:18.395 --> 00:35:20.899
- So the ending is actually sad

559
00:35:20.962 --> 00:35:24.243
because they all chose
to remain in their traps.

560
00:35:24.771 --> 00:35:27.715
- It’s supposed to be a sad ending.

561
00:35:29.380 --> 00:35:32.990
- The child grew up properly,

562
00:35:33.045 --> 00:35:38.059
but everyone is trapped
in their own miseries.

563
00:35:38.130 --> 00:35:39.643
- Well that happens.

564
00:35:42.742 --> 00:35:46.403
If that’s what you’re going to do,

565
00:35:47.398 --> 00:35:50.122
then you have to be clear about it.

566
00:35:50.621 --> 00:35:57.450
It will therefore be in the framing
of the characters themselves.

567
00:35:57.506 --> 00:35:59.544
How you define them.

568
00:35:59.841 --> 00:36:03.278
Because right now, everything feels so sudden.

569
00:36:03.342 --> 00:36:07.792
Why's the mayor suddenly good?
Why'd this suddenly happen?

570
00:36:07.863 --> 00:36:09.280
Those kinds of things.

571
00:36:11.929 --> 00:36:14.754
The objective
 needs to be singular.

572
00:36:14.779 --> 00:36:16.809
It’s either the character
gets it or not.

573
00:36:16.857 --> 00:36:21.141
The characters can't suddenly
just change decisions.

574
00:36:26.088 --> 00:36:28.133
80% of the play

575
00:36:28.219 --> 00:36:33.365
they seem to be very determined
to do everything they promised to do.

576
00:36:33.390 --> 00:36:35.643
Remember our lesson on speech acts?

577
00:36:35.793 --> 00:36:38.493
When Victor declared,

578
00:36:38.540 --> 00:36:44.242
"I can and I will renounce
priesthood for Sarah."

579
00:36:44.610 --> 00:36:47.548
And then in one swift scene,

580
00:36:47.876 --> 00:36:49.953
"I'll just go back to priesthood"

581
00:36:50.015 --> 00:36:52.527
"because my child lived."

582
00:36:53.035 --> 00:36:54.720
It's a bit...

583
00:36:54.888 --> 00:36:56.488
There's an imbalance, right?

584
00:36:56.693 --> 00:37:03.076
That’s the kind of thing
that’s done just to align with the ending.

585
00:37:03.818 --> 00:37:05.825
- Actually, the statement is good

586
00:37:05.872 --> 00:37:11.063
because in truth, a lot of people
continue even within their traps.

587
00:37:11.271 --> 00:37:16.537
- Since that’s your ending,
I think the needed setup is,

588
00:37:17.001 --> 00:37:20.974
- the next stage is the power
of the institutions.

589
00:37:22.469 --> 00:37:24.328
- The power of the church,

590
00:37:24.414 --> 00:37:30.881
- the communal beliefs that trap
 individuals in situations they don’t want.

591
00:37:30.986 --> 00:37:32.838
- How do you set up that power?

592
00:37:32.892 --> 00:37:37.068
- That even Victor,

593
00:37:37.178 --> 00:37:41.249
who sings about not giving up
even when getting burnt,

594
00:37:41.379 --> 00:37:43.860
and yet gives up...

595
00:37:44.459 --> 00:37:46.453
- What are those traps?

596
00:37:47.594 --> 00:37:52.354
- I don't know the play's scope,
but if that's the message

597
00:37:53.380 --> 00:37:56.116
- Then you’re talking
about powerful institutions

598
00:37:56.165 --> 00:38:02.208
that individuals can’t seem to get away from.

599
00:38:05.341 --> 00:38:08.744
- It’s a different kind of melodrama,
it's no longer drama.

600
00:38:08.830 --> 00:38:10.435
- We're pushing
the limits of the genre.

601
00:38:10.577 --> 00:38:13.635
- 'Cause it's usually very liberating.

602
00:38:14.034 --> 00:38:17.445
It works for a sarsuwela.

603
00:38:23.822 --> 00:38:26.288
The definition of the characters

604
00:38:26.478 --> 00:38:28.363
are falling apart,

605
00:38:28.411 --> 00:38:29.902
are unstable.

606
00:38:31.176 --> 00:38:33.204
- It changed in the middle somewhere.

607
00:38:33.678 --> 00:38:36.580
- In sarsuwelas,
they can pursue that...

608
00:38:37.673 --> 00:38:45.462
Even I can’t see the promise
that Ellen (offscreen) is looking for.

609
00:38:47.750 --> 00:38:50.735
Because in the end,
Mauro disappeared.

610
00:38:50.781 --> 00:38:54.375
And he’s the only one
who sees everything in that light.

611
00:38:54.524 --> 00:38:56.166
And he’s not a revolutionary.

612
00:38:56.205 --> 00:38:58.546
He’s also an outcast
in a sense

613
00:38:58.948 --> 00:39:02.165
because he’s gay, right?

614
00:39:02.947 --> 00:39:07.556
So he’s not taken seriously,
which is a nice touch.

615
00:39:07.991 --> 00:39:12.242
He’s like Cassandra
who’s telling the truth,

616
00:39:12.429 --> 00:39:15.625
but nobody takes him seriously
just because he’s gay.

617
00:39:16.885 --> 00:39:19.355
Maybe he should have a song on that.

